04276nam a22006495i 9780814769454DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19861986nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147694547 a10.18574/97808147694542doi  a(DE-B1597)548387  a(OCoLC)1163877859  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD810.J4bC68 1986 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a940.53/15/039242191 aRittner, Carol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Courage to Care /cCarol Rittner, Sondra Myers. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1986] 4c©1986  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tODETTE MEYERS -- tJOHTJE VOS -- tMARION PRITCHARD -- tMAX ROTHSCHILD -- tHERMANN GRAEBE/ MARIA BOBROW -- tIRENE OPDYKE -- tEMANUEL TANAY -- tJOHN WEIDNER -- tGABY COHEN -- tIVO HERZER -- tCHAIM ASA -- tLEO EITINGER -- tJØRGEN KIELER -- tLEO GOLDBERGER -- tINTRODUCTION -- tMAGDA TROCMÉ -- tMajor Julius Schmahling -- tTHREE SURVIVORS: Hans Solomon, Hanne Liebmann, Rudy Appel -- tWhy Were There So Few? -- tExamples of Heroism -- tTEN QUESTIONS -- tThey Could Do No Other -- tThe Courage to Care -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe extraordinary story of a few non-Jews who risked their lives to rescue and protect Jews from Nazi persecution in Europe during World War II is told in The Courage to Care. It features the first person accounts of rescuers and of survivors whose stories address the basic issue of individual responsibility: the notion that one person can act-and that those actions can make a difference. These rescuers are true heroes, but modest ones. They did a thousand ordinary things-opening doors, hiding and feeding strangers, keeping secrets-in an extraordinary time. For this, they are known as "Righteous Among the Nations of the World." The rescuers and survivors are from many countries in Europe-Italy, the Netherlands, Denmark, Norway, France, Bulgaria, Poland, Germany-and they tell their stories with simplicity and dignity. Each story is interwoven with old snapshots of rescuers and survivors, their homes, their hiding places, and the communities in which they lived. Noted author, teacher, and human rights activist, Elie Wiesel, helps us to ask: "what made these people different?" He points out how those who helped Jews during the Holocaust "changed history" by their actions. The Courage to Care reminds readers of the power of individual action. This compelling book is the companion volume to the award-winning film, The Courage to Care, and includes the personal narratives of the same persons in the film and many others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aRighteous Gentiles in the Holocaust. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescuezFrancezLe Chambon-sur-Lignon. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescue. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aMyers, Sondra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814769454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814769454.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK